05887nam a22009615i 9781512824827DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815128248277 a10.9783/97815128248272doi  a(DE-B1597)650758  a(OCoLC)1378934423  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0400002bisacsh1 aSterett, Susan M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLitigating the Pandemic :bDisaster Cascades in Court /cSusan M. Sterett. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Studies in Risk and Disaster00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. What Are Disaster Cascades? -- tChapter 2. Democratic Backsliding and Litigation -- tChapter 3. Courts, Meaning, and Instrumental Effectiveness -- tChapter 4. Tsunamis, Explosions, and Misdirecting Metaphors -- tChapter 5. Government Authority, Civil Liberties, and Mass Incarceration -- tConclusion: Courts and Accepting Loss in a Pandemic -- tAppendix: A Note on Data and Methods -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs officials scrambled in 2020 to manage the spread of COVID, the reverberations of the crisis reached well beyond immediate public health concerns. The governance problems that emerged in the pandemic would be problems in other climate-related disasters, too.Many of these governance problems wound up in court. Businesses filed insurance claims for lost commerce; when the claims were denied, some companies sued. Defense attorneys tried to get inmates released from prison, citing dangerous living conditions. As state governments ordered closures and otherwise tried to adapt, interest organizations that had long sought to limit government authority challenged them in court. Political officials railed against litigation they argued would stop businesses from reopening. The United States, like other countries, governs partly through litigation, and litigation is one way of seeing the multiple governance failures during the pandemic.Drawing on databases of cases filed, news reports, and the websites of advocacy groups and law firms, Susan M. Sterett argues that governing during the pandemic, or in any disaster, must include the human institutions intertwined with the effects of the virus. Those institutions reveal problems well beyond the reach of technical expertise. Failures in private insurance as a way of governing risk, conflicts about the primacy of religion, government authority, and health, are problems that predated the pandemic and will persist in future disasters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aDisastersxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aDisastersxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Disasters & Disaster Relief.2bisacsh  a2020.  aCOVID.  aPandemic.  aSARS COV-2.  acivil rights.  aclimate change.  aclimate covid and expertise.  aclosures due to COVID.  aconservative legal movements.  acourts.  adisaster cascade.  adisaster studies.  aexperts expertise.  aface masks.  afree exercise of religion.  agovernance.  agovernment authority.  agovernment officials.  ainsurance.  aliability.  amandates.  amass incarceration.  apandemic politics.  apolitics of courts.  aprivate insurance.  apublic health.  arule of law.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 E